!! Architecture

!!! Widget tree & context

`<$statewrap>` creates a `statewrapContext` object on its widget instance. All descendant widgets find this context by walking up the `parentWidget` chain — the same pattern used by json-dsl's `getJsonContext()`.

```
<$statewrap>                    ← creates statewrapContext
  <$statewrap-rule>             ← registers in context.rules[]
    <$action-statewrap-set>     ← rule's action children
  </$statewrap-rule>
  <$list>                       ← any depth of nesting
    <$button>
      <$action-statewrap-set>   ← finds context via parent walk
    </$button>
  </$list>
</$statewrap>
```

!!! Context object

```javascript
{
  prefix: "$:/state/rimir/statewrap/<instid>/",
  channels: {
    "channel-name": {
      default: "",
      tiddler: "$:/state/rimir/statewrap/<instid>/channel-name"
    }
  },
  rules: [{ when: "channel-name", widget: <StatewrapRuleWidget> }],
  wiki: $tw.wiki,
  _applyingRules: false
}
```

!!! Data flow

# User clicks button containing `<$action-statewrap-set channel="X" value="V"/>`
# Action widget walks parent chain to find `statewrapContext`
# Looks up channel → gets state tiddler path
# Writes value via `wiki.setText()`
# Iterates `context.rules` — for each rule where `when === "X"`, calls `rule.widget.invokeRuleActions()`
# Rule's child action widgets execute (e.g., clear another channel)
# `_applyingRules` flag prevents nested rules from firing (single level only)

!!! State tiddler naming

```
$:/state/rimir/statewrap/<instid>/<channel-name>
```

If `instid` is not provided, TW's `qualify` mechanism generates a unique ID based on the widget's position in the render tree.

